 *1255752306*Re: Is a blog copyrighted?
 Re: http://loftwork.com/special/web_copyright01.aspx
 
 >>
 You are always showing pictures of your cute cat on your blog. One day, you receive an e-mail from a friend informing you that some of the photos are on a stranger's blog. You are completely delighted to see that they seem to clearly state that they were taken from your blog, and they also include a comment that says, "They are so cute, I had to introduce them.
 
 　Surprisingly, however, the friend said this.
 
 　You said, "The photos and text you post on your blog are clear works of authorship, and if you quote them without permission, you are infringing on their copyrights. You are, from a legal standpoint, infringing on my rights."
 <<
 
 >>
 Conventional copyright law is outdated
 
 　In this way, you can see how the existing copyright laws are not suited to the Internet age.
 　A person who posts a photo of his or her cat on his or her blog is treated as the "author" of a "work" of art, a photo of a beloved cat, and is subject to protection under copyright law, regardless of whether the person is aware of the fact that he or she has posted the photo. Therefore, if the work is reproduced without permission, the copyright has been infringed.
 <<
 
 >>
 A happy relationship has been established between the user who posted a photo of his cat on his blog and the user who, in good faith, featured that photo on his own blog. However, from the perspective of the current copyright law, these two people are the victim of an infringement and the perpetrator of an infringement.
 <<
 
 No, you can just go to the citee's site and write "Thank you for the introduction" when the unauthorized citation is discovered. The person who reprinted the article should not reprint it without permission. The person who reprinted it should not reprint it without permission, but just ask "Can I reprint it?
 
 It's one thing to have rights, it's another to exercise them. If the law is such that the right is not granted in this situation, it would be impossible to say to remove it even if the photo is quoted in the same way and the comment is "Here's the woman who took the picture in the mirror in the corner of this picture with her spunky face HAHAHA".
 
 I don't think copyright law is a perfect fit for the current situation, but I think the current copyright law is the right one, at least in this case.
 
