 <body>>It is one thing to have rights and another to exercise them. <BR><BR>That's exactly right<BR><BR>If you are not familiar with the law, you may have the following assumptions. <br><br>1. Laws are effective only by their existence<br>2. Laws transcend time<br><br>1. To put it plainly, if you do not go to court and cry yourself to sleep, <br>no matter how unreasonable the crime, the law will not bring the offender to justice. <br>Also, the rights granted are meaningless if not exercised. <BR>In the case of property rights, you say, "This belongs to me," in the case of human rights, you insist, "I have human rights, so protect them," and so on. <BR><BR>On the contrary, if you do not exercise your rights, you are in a state of "tacit consent"<BR>so if you decide that there is no need to forcefully apply your rights or the law,<BR>I don't think you need to do anything in particular. <BR><BR>About #2. <BR>Laws are time sensitive. <BR>First of all, it takes time to make them. <br>It is not unusual for a law to be out of step with the current situation after it has been passed. <br>It takes time to make it known. <br>It takes a long time to get the word out, and by the time you realize, "Oh, there's such a law! <br>It takes time to apply the law. <BR><BR>It takes time to apply. You have to consult a lawyer, file a lawsuit, go to trial, and receive a judgment before it takes effect. <BR><BR>It seems that the text of the aforementioned blog assumes a world where <BR>"laws act as if they are automatic, and <BR>there is little time taken to create, disseminate, and apply them. <BR><BR>This is hardly realistic. <br><br>So, when copyright infringement actually occurs, we have no choice but to do what we can with the current law<br>by expanding the interpretation of the current copyright law, by looking for similar cases in the past, etc.<br>As a result, we are forced to do what we can with the current law. <br>As a result, when "the current law is inadequate" and "it is criminal by all accounts,"<br>then the decision is finally made to "make a new law. <br><br>"The existing copyright law is outdated" - that's right, the law always follows. </body>
